<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="367" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,368,395]" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Presently, seven species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jacobi" authorityYear="1910" box="[669,755,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[669,755,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group are known (
<bibRefCitation author="Linnavuori, R." box="[962,1161,369,395]" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" pagination="1 - 17" refId="ref7467" refString="Linnavuori, R. (1978) Studies on the family Cicadellidae (Homoptera, Auchenorrhyncha). 1. A revision of the Macropsinae of the Ethiopian Region. Acta Entomologica Fennica, 33, 1 - 17." type="journal article" year="1978">Linnavuori, 1978</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jacobi" authorityYear="1910" box="[1209,1331,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[1209,1331,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">M. simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
head and pronotum more angular, pygofer process shorter, style bent inwards; also, it is somewhat larger; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1978" box="[1249,1349,406,431]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas">
<emphasis box="[1249,1349,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">M. gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1978" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamellaris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">M. lamellaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are much larger; in 
<emphasis box="[490,744,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Metcalf" authorityYear="1966" box="[490,600,441,467]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chinai">M. chinai</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[611,744,442,467]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capensis">M. capensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1955" box="[799,974,441,467]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kanongensis">
<emphasis box="[799,974,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">M. kanongensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
penis stem gradually tapering apically in side view (
<figureCitation box="[273,411,476,503]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–81" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1732,1757]" captionTargetBox="[258,1328,184,1711]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[256,1332,166,1712]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 41–81. 41–43—Macropsis simplex Jacobi; 44–48—M. tincta Tisheсhkin sp. n.; 49—M. chinai Metcalf; 50—M. kanongensis Evans; 51—M. capensis (Cogan); 52–55—M. tuberculata (Linnavuori); 56–58—M. turneri China; 59–62—M. viridofulgida Tisheсhkin sp. n.; 63–67— M. hippodameia Linnavuori; 68–70—M. minuscula Linnavuori; 71–72—M. bussaensis Linnavuori; 73–76—M. thargelia Linnavuori; 77–79—M. nigrosignata (Stål); 80–81—M. bitaeniata Linnavuori. 41–42, 55, 59–60—2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 43, 61–62—female 7th sternite; 44—male 2nd abdominal apodemes; 45, 49–51, 63–64, 68, 71, 73, 77, 80—penis, lateral view; 46—pygofer process, lateral view; 47—pygofer processes, back view; 48, 67, 70, 76, 79, 81—style; 52, 57—head, pro-, and mesonotum, dorsal view; 53, 56—forewing; 54, 58—female genital segments, ventral view; 65–66, 69, 72, 74–75, 78—style tip. 49–50, 63–81—after Linnavuori (1978), 51—after Theron (1970), 56–58—after China (1925)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772393/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">Figs. 49–51</figureCitation>
); 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1978" box="[430,540,477,503]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bakeri">
<emphasis box="[430,540,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">M. bakeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known only from female 
<typeStatus box="[831,929,477,503]" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">holotype</typeStatus>
is distinctly larger and more robust.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,613,513,539]" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,575]" box="[199,613,513,539]" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,513,539]" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">Host.</emphasis>
“On shrubs including 
<taxonomicName box="[516,594,513,539]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[516,594,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">Acacia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="367" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,575]" box="[199,1437,549,575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,549,575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">Etymology.</emphasis>
The Latin word “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tishechkin" authorityYear="2019" box="[514,574,550,575]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tincta">
<emphasis box="[514,574,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">tincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” means “speckled”; thus, the name indicates the colouring feature of this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,657,719]" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">
The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="China" authorityYear="1925" box="[203,281,658,683]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turneri">
<emphasis box="[203,281,658,683]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="367">turneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. Veins of forewing with black tubercles, ovipositor short, only slightly extends beyond the end of genital segment.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
